Natural selection is the process in which individuals with helpful traits survive and reproduce more successfully than others, allowing them to pass those traits on to their offspring. Over multiple generations, this differential survival and reproduction gradually shapes the overall characteristics of populations, enabling them to adapt more effectively to their environment.

This occurs because helpful traits (those that improve survival or reproductive success in a given setting) become more common over time, while less helpful ones tend to diminish, resulting in populations that are better suited to their surroundings. 

\confidence{70}
